'''Thelonious''' "'''Thelo'''" '''Gerard Aasgaard''' (born 2 May 2002) is a professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[Scottish Premiership]] club [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]. Born in England, he represents the [[Norway national football team|Norway national team]].

==Early life and youth career==
Aasgaard was born in [[Liverpool]] in 2002. Both of his parents have musical backgrounds; his father Jonathan is a professional [[cellist]], and his mother Georgina is a music and health practitioner.<ref name="Feature: How music is helping Thelo Aasgaard become pitch perfect">{{cite web |title=Feature: How music is helping Thelo Aasgaard become pitch perfect |url=https://www.efl.com/news/2022/february/feature-how-music-is-helping-aasgaard-become-pitch-perfect/ |publisher=The English Football League |access-date=15 December 2024}}</ref> Aasgaard joined the youth academy of [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] at the age of 14, having previously been a part of the youth set-up at [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Thelo Aasgaard: A Proud Moment For Me And My Family |url=https://wiganathletic.com/news/2020/november/Thelo-Aasgaard-A-proud-moment-for-me-and-my-family-/ |publisher=Wigan Athletic |access-date=15 December 2024 |date=21 November 2020}}</ref> and signed scholarship forms with the club in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=10 Youngsters Offered Scholarships For Next Season |url=https://wiganathletic.com/news/2017/december/10-youngsters-offered-scholarships-for-next-season/ |publisher=Wigan Athletic |access-date=15 December 2024 |date=21 December 2017}}</ref> His progress in the academy ranks was interrupted by injuries during the following two seasons,<ref name="Feature: How music is helping Thelo Aasgaard become pitch perfect" /> but he impressed enough for his scholarship deal to be extended for a third year in 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=U23 and U18 Retained List |url=https://wiganathletic.com/news/2020/may/U23-and-U18-Retained-List-2020-/ |publisher=Wigan Athletic |access-date=16 December 2024 |date=6 May 2020}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Wigan Athletic===
As a result of Wigan being put into administration in the [[2019–20 Wigan Athletic F.C. season|2019–20 season]], and the team's subsequent relegation from the [[EFL Championship|Championship]], Aasgaard was promoted to the club's first-team squad along with several other academy players for their [[2020–21 Wigan Athletic F.C. season|2020–21]] League One campaign.

Aasgaard made his professional debut with Wigan in a 1–0 [[EFL League One]] loss at home to [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]] on 20 October 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uk.soccerway.com/matches/2020/10/20/england/league-one/wigan-athletic-football-club/peterborough-united-fc/3345884/|title=Wigan Athletic vs. Peterborough United - 20 October 2020 - Soccerway|website=uk.soccerway.com|accessdate=20 October 2020}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Wigan in a 2–1 defeat against [[Oxford United]] on 21 November 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title="Wigan 1-2 Oxford" |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54941054 |accessdate=21 November 2020}}</ref> In January 2021, Aasgaard signed his first professional contract with Wigan, signing until the summer of 2023.<ref>{{cite web |title=Thelo Aasgaard pens first professional contract |url= https://wiganathletic.com/news/2021/january/New-Contract-Thelo-Aasgaard-pens-first-professional-contract/ |website=Wigan Athletic Official Site |date= 11 January 2021 |accessdate=11 January 2021 }}</ref> He ended his first season having played 35 times in all competitions, including 13 league starts, scoring three goals.<ref name="auto">{{soccerbase season|133855|season=2020|accessdate=9 May 2021}}</ref>

After the start of the 2021–22 season, Aasgaard signed an improved four-and-a-half-year contract, running until June 2026.<ref>{{cite web |title= Wigan Athletic star agrees new long-term deal |url= https://www.wigantoday.net/sport/football/wigan-athletic-star-agrees-new-long-term-deal-3489718/ |website=Wigan Today |date= 9 December 2021 |accessdate=9 December 2021}}</ref> In July 2023, he signed a further contract extension until 2028.<ref>{{cite web |title=Thelo Aasgaard: Wigan Athletic midfielder signs new deal |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66270113 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=15 December 2024 |date=21 July 2023}}</ref>

=== Luton Town ===
On 28 January 2025, Aasgaard signed for [[EFL Championship|Championship]] side [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lutontown.co.uk/en/news/thelo-aasgaard-joins-the-hatters|title=Thelo Aasgaard joins the Hatters!|website=www.lutontown.co.uk|date=28 January 2025|accessdate=29 January 2025}}</ref> On 1 February 2025, Aasgaard made his debut for Luton in a 1–1 draw against [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]].

=== Rangers ===
After Luton’s relegation from the Championship, Aasgaard joined [[Scottish Premiership]] club [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] on 5 July 2025 for an undisclosed fee which was reported to be £3.5 million. He signed a contract running until 2029.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-07-05 |title=Rangers buy Norway's Thelo Aasgaard from Luton Town |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cpd1jggz5wzo |access-date=2025-07-05 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> After an early injury ruled him out of the opening league and European fixtures, Thelo finally made his debut coming on as a second half substitute in a 4–2 victory over Alloa Athletic in the Premier Sports League Cup.

==International career==
Aasgaard was born in Liverpool, England, and is of Norwegian descent through his father, and of French descent through his mother.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wigantoday.net/sport/football/wigan-athletic-duo-receive-international-call-ups-3359837|title=Wigan Athletic duo receive international call-ups|website=www.wigantoday.net|date=25 August 2021 }}</ref>

He represented the [[Norway national under-16 football team|Norway under-16 team]] three times in 2018.<ref>{{NFF|3408341}}</ref>

In August 2021, Aasgaard was called up to the [[Norway national under-20 football team|Norway under-20 team]] for the first time, and made his debut on the right of midfield in their 1–1 draw with [[Germany]] under-20 on 6 September 2021.<ref>{{cite web |title="GER 1-1 NOR / Germany-Norway / Match Summary" |url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/jTZ4Z8Hl/#match-summary/lineups |website=FlashScore.com |accessdate=6 September 2021 }}</ref>

On the 9th September, 2025, Aasgaard scored four goals for Norway off the bench at the 65th minute against [[Moldova national football team|Moldova]] in an 11–1 victory in the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|UEFA World Cup Qualifiers]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Norway vs. Moldova Box Score and Stats - September 09, 2025 |url=https://www.foxsports.com/soccer/wcq-uefa-norway-vs-moldova-sep-09-2025-game-boxscore-615087?tab=boxscore |access-date=2025-09-09 |website=www.foxsports.com |language=en-US}}</ref>

